327
00:29:41,279 --> 00:29:42,769
Didn't you love me?

328
00:30:25,990 --> 00:30:27,457
Look, there he is.

329
00:30:28,259 --> 00:30:30,056
There's your grandfather.

330
00:30:30,962 --> 00:30:32,088
Barton.

331
00:30:32,831 --> 00:30:35,425
Hello, Frank. How you doing?
Good to see you.

332
00:30:35,567 --> 00:30:38,434
- Let me take that.
- Hello. How you doing, Candy?

333
00:30:38,703 --> 00:30:41,467
I guess you don't remember
your old granddad?

334
00:30:43,074 --> 00:30:44,473
Right this way.

335
00:30:44,776 --> 00:30:48,473
You didn't have to come way out here.
We could have met later, at the hotel.

336
00:30:48,580 --> 00:30:51,071
I just didn't like the idea
of you coming in alone.

337
00:30:51,182 --> 00:30:52,877
How long you plan to stay in town?

338
00:30:52,984 --> 00:30:55,612
I guess we could
have the funeral tomorrow...

339
00:30:55,887 --> 00:30:58,651
but Juliana's parents
might want to come in from Arizona.

340
00:30:58,756 --> 00:31:02,783
Then there's that sister in Vancouver.
I don't know just how it's going to work out.

341
00:31:02,894 --> 00:31:05,920
- All right. What hotel are you staying in?
- Park Plaza.

342
00:31:06,531 --> 00:31:10,160
You know, I was even thinking
about going out to that old house again.

343
00:31:10,535 --> 00:31:13,026
I still have the key, after all these years.

344
00:31:13,471 --> 00:31:17,407
Juliana used to make a big fuss
about never having changed the locks.

345
00:31:17,876 --> 00:31:19,867
I could never understand why.

346
00:31:20,311 --> 00:31:23,940
Maybe it's because she really couldn't admit
that we were finished.

347
00:31:25,216 --> 00:31:27,616
When I think about you and Nola...

348
00:31:28,319 --> 00:31:32,278
and this sweet child having to go through
the same heartaches we went through...

349
00:31:32,390 --> 00:31:34,187
it's enough to make you cry.

350
00:31:35,960 --> 00:31:37,291
Yes, it is.

351
00:32:17,468 --> 00:32:20,767
I'm here to see Mr. Jan Hartog.

352
00:32:38,690 --> 00:32:40,988
Come in. Right in.

353
00:32:48,199 --> 00:32:50,963
Sit down. I'll be right there.

354
00:32:55,773 --> 00:32:57,934
Sit down. I'll be there in a second.

355
00:33:01,145 --> 00:33:03,409
Goddamn son of a bitch.

356
00:33:10,488 --> 00:33:11,682
Okay.

357
00:33:27,505 --> 00:33:28,802
That's my...

358
00:33:29,774 --> 00:33:31,674
heart, over there on the floor.

359
00:33:32,310 --> 00:33:34,437
- Your heart?
- My second heart.

360
00:33:35,646 --> 00:33:39,639
Your first heart
makes your blood circulate, right?

361
00:33:40,718 --> 00:33:42,948
But what about your lymphatic fluids?

362
00:33:44,255 --> 00:33:45,449
I don't know.

363
00:33:45,857 --> 00:33:50,055
Movement, walking and running, fucking,
rolling on the floor, anything.

364
00:33:50,661 --> 00:33:54,188
People have this whole other system
they don't even know about.

365
00:33:54,365 --> 00:33:57,823
The lymphatic system,
it's like the blood system...

366
00:33:57,935 --> 00:34:01,871
with its own style of veins and arteries...

367
00:34:02,640 --> 00:34:03,937
but no heart.

368
00:34:04,909 --> 00:34:07,571
You have to keep moving
to get it to circulate.

369
00:34:08,613 --> 00:34:13,380
And they've just given me pills.
They do that every day.

370
00:34:15,219 --> 00:34:18,711
And I've got to move them
through the lymphatic system.

371
00:34:20,792 --> 00:34:22,987
Goddamn it.

372
00:34:29,000 --> 00:34:30,490
Pardon my sweat.

373
00:34:31,302 --> 00:34:33,600
I'm gonna take a bath, real soon.

374
00:34:35,039 --> 00:34:39,100
So, Mr. Carveth...

375
00:34:39,610 --> 00:34:40,975
how did you get my name?

376
00:34:41,079 --> 00:34:43,206
My lawyer knows your lawyer.

377
00:34:43,314 --> 00:34:45,179
I see. I get it.

378
00:34:45,283 --> 00:34:48,775
Is your lawyer
preparing a case against Raglan, too?

379
00:34:49,554 --> 00:34:50,851
Basically, yes.

380
00:34:51,522 --> 00:34:54,855
- Slightly different from yours.
- How different?

381
00:34:56,461 --> 00:34:58,929
My wife is still in therapy with Raglan.

382
00:35:00,098 --> 00:35:04,262
I'm claiming psychological damage,
not physiological.

383
00:35:04,869 --> 00:35:07,667
I see. Give him some more time
with your wife...

384
00:35:08,172 --> 00:35:11,232
and you'll be able to claim
physiological damage, too.

385
00:35:13,177 --> 00:35:15,475
Wouldn't this look impressive in court?

386
00:35:18,916 --> 00:35:20,440
Do you like it? I do.

387
00:35:21,786 --> 00:35:25,347
That's Raglan. That's psychoplasmics...

388
00:35:25,723 --> 00:35:28,283
and it's called lymphosarcoma.

389
00:35:29,260 --> 00:35:31,228
And it's spreading.

390
00:35:32,697 --> 00:35:35,291
It's a form of cancer
of the lymphatic system.

391
00:35:35,967 --> 00:35:37,730
You blame Raglan for that?

392
00:35:38,903 --> 00:35:40,336
Raglan did it.

393
00:35:42,173 --> 00:35:44,971
Raglan encouraged my body...

394
00:35:46,377 --> 00:35:48,470
to revolt against me.

395
00:35:49,614 --> 00:35:50,774
And it did.

396
00:35:51,182 --> 00:35:54,913
I have a small revolution on my hands...

397
00:35:55,553 --> 00:35:58,249
and I'm not putting it down
very successfully.

398
00:35:58,956 --> 00:36:02,517
Then your lawyer really thinks
he can prove Raglan's responsible?

399
00:36:02,727 --> 00:36:06,094
Are you kidding me?
You can't prove something like that in court.

400
00:36:06,197 --> 00:36:09,758
Right from square one,
you're into, what, metaphysics?

401
00:36:12,770 --> 00:36:15,364
How do you know
I'm not going to get cancer at age 32...

402
00:36:15,473 --> 00:36:19,000
whether I'd gone into
psychoplasmics therapy or not?

403
00:36:20,011 --> 00:36:22,809
No, we'd get laughed out of court.

404
00:36:23,748 --> 00:36:26,182
Then why are you going into court?

405
00:36:27,285 --> 00:36:28,582
Revenge.

406
00:36:33,124 --> 00:36:36,719
Even if we lose, people will get nervous
about psychoplasmics.

407
00:36:36,827 --> 00:36:39,057
It will be bad publicity.

408
00:36:41,265 --> 00:36:43,825
They won't even remember
whether we won or lost.

409
00:36:43,935 --> 00:36:46,130
They'll just remember the slogan:

410
00:36:46,904 --> 00:36:50,431
"Psychoplasmics can cause cancer."

411
00:36:51,342 --> 00:36:52,639
Catchy.

412
00:36:55,746 --> 00:36:57,475
Is that going to help?

413
00:37:01,586 --> 00:37:02,553
Maybe.

414
00:37:03,387 --> 00:37:04,479
I'm not alone.

415
00:37:04,589 --> 00:37:08,150
I'm in touch with a lot of people
who did psychoplasmics.

416
00:37:10,161 --> 00:37:11,856
We might form a club.

417
00:37:15,032 --> 00:37:17,193
I want to help you.

418
00:37:19,503 --> 00:37:21,095
Okay. Thanks.

419
00:37:41,492 --> 00:37:42,754
Dr. Raglan?

420
00:37:45,663 --> 00:37:46,630
Yes?

421
00:37:47,064 --> 00:37:50,090
I'm Barton Kelly, Nola Carveth's father.

422
00:37:51,302 --> 00:37:52,633
Glad to meet you.

423
00:37:52,737 --> 00:37:55,570
I'm sorry to accost you like this...

424
00:37:55,673 --> 00:37:58,506
but your receptionist wasn't too helpful.

425
00:37:59,010 --> 00:38:01,410
She probably knew I was on my way to...

426
00:38:01,512 --> 00:38:04,504
Did you know
that Nola's mother died yesterday?

427
00:38:04,615 --> 00:38:06,082
That she was murdered?

428
00:38:06,284 --> 00:38:08,343
Yes, the police spoke to me.

429
00:38:08,919 --> 00:38:11,683
- Then you've told her.
- No, I haven't.

430
00:38:13,057 --> 00:38:15,958
That's why I'm here, to tell her.

431
00:38:16,560 --> 00:38:19,996
Mr. Kelly, your wife's death
